===Noun===
'''plant''' (''plural:'' '''[[plants]]''')

#{{botany}}: A living [[organism]] of the kingdom ''Plantae'', a multicellular [[eukaryote]] that includes [[chloroplast]]s in its [[cell]]s and produces [[egg]] and [[sperm]] cells within protective sterile structures.
#{{botany}}: A living organism of the kingdom ''Plantae'' or of the division ''Chlorophyta'' (green algae), a eukaryote that includes double-membraned chloroplasts in its cells containing chlorophyll ''a'' and ''b'', or any organism genetically related to such an organism. 
#A living organism that includes [[chlorophyll]] in its cells, including [[alga]]e and some [[bacteria]].
#A living organism that is not an animal, including [[fungi]].

====Usage notes====
The scientific definition of what should be considered a plant changed dramatically during the 20th century with the rise of advanced micrscopy techniques and DNA sequencing.  As a result, there are many books still in print that use the older definition, as well as newer books that use a more recent definition. The system most often used prior to microscopy practically divided all known living organisms into two groups: ''Plantae'' and ''Animalia''. By the end of the 20th century, many thousands of miscroscopic species were known that did not fit into these categories, and the establishment of genetic sequencing databases and the evolutionary theory led to a new system of classification based on descent ([[cladistics]]). In particular, bacteria, algae, and fungi are no longer considered plants by botanists (see definition 1 or 2), though they are still called plants by ecologists (see definition 3) because of their shared ability to carry out photosynthesis.  The general public (for whom evolutionary hypotheses of relationships do not affect their perception of what constitutes a plant) typically uses definition 4.

